d from the medieval given name. <i>Piers</i> was revived in the mid-20th century, perhaps partly under the influence of  William Langland's  great rambling medieval poem Piers Plowman (  1367–86 ), in which the character of Piers symbolizes the virtues of hard work, honesty, and fairness."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":45,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":54,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Piers II Goldington was born in 1170, in Goldington, Bedfordshire, England, his father, Peter de Goldington, was 35 and his mother, Eva de Roppersley, was 40. He had at least 1 son and 3 daughters with Jeanne De La De Goldington Saussaye. He died in 1252, at the age of 82."},"et":{"1170–1252":"1170–1252","1155–1175":"1155–1175","1173–1275":"1173–1275","1172–Female":"1172–Surnud","1210–1300":"1210–1300","1200–1252":"1200–1252","1226–Female":"1226–Surnud","1228–Female":"1228–Surnud","1135–1194":"1135–1194","1130–1200":"1130–1200","1275":"1275","1252":"1252","1175":"1175","1130":"1130","1173":"1173","1194":"1194","1172":"1172","1170":"117